Installation and Navigation of Visual Studio Code (VS Code)
Installation of VS Code
Download and Install: Visit VS Code website, download for Windows, run VSCodeSetup.exe.
Prerequisites: Admin privileges, 64-bit Windows OS.
First-time Setup
Settings Sync: Sign in with Microsoft or GitHub account.
Theme: File > Preferences > Color Theme.
Font Size: File > Preferences > Settings, search "Font Size".
Extensions: Ctrl+Shift+X, install Prettier, ESLint, Python, Live Server.
User Interface Overview
Activity Bar: Access views (Explorer, Search, Source Control, Run and Debug, Extensions).
Side Bar: Displays views based on Activity Bar selection.
Editor Group: Central area for editing, supports split view.
Status Bar: Shows Git branch, line/column number, language mode, notifications.
Command Palette
Access: Ctrl+Shift+P (Windows) or Cmd+Shift+P (Mac).
Common Tasks: Open file, go to symbol, format document.
Extensions in VS Code
Role: Add features, languages, debuggers, tools.
Management: Ctrl+Shift+X, enable/disable/uninstall.
Essential Extensions: Live Server, Prettier, ESLint, GitLens.
Integrated Terminal
Open: Ctrl+ (backtick) or View > Terminal.
Advantages: Interact with environment, run commands/scripts, support multiple instances/shells.
File and Folder Management
Create: Right-click in Explorer, select "New File/New Folder".
Open: Drag and drop, or File > Open File/Open Folder.
Navigate: Ctrl+P, use Explorer view.
Settings and Preferences
Access: File > Preferences > Settings or Ctrl+,.
Examples: Change theme (search "Color Theme"), adjust font size (search "Font Size"), modify keybindings (Ctrl+K Ctrl+S).
Debugging in VS Code
Setup: Ensure launch.json is configured, set breakpoints.
Start: Run and Debug icon, select configuration, click play.
Features: Variable inspection, watch expressions, call stack navigation, step-through execution.
Using Source Control
Initialize Repository: Open project folder, Source Control icon, initialize repository.
Commits: Stage changes, enter commit message, commit.
Push to GitHub: Set up remote repository, push changes via command palette or terminal.
